  "notes": "Tetum (Tetun Praça / Tetun Dili). Austronesian language (Malayo-Polynesian); co-official language of East Timor alongside Portuguese. ~800,000 speakers including L2. Tetun Praça (urban Dili creolized variety) is the official variety, heavily influenced by Portuguese. KEY FEATURES: (1) FINAL OBSTRUENTS: final -k may realize as [ʔ] (glottal stop) — Austronesian feature. (2) PALATAL CONSONANTS: lh=[ʎ], nh=[ɲ], x=[ʃ], j=[dʒ] — borrowed graphemic conventions from Portuguese. (3) NASAL VELAR: ng=[ŋ] may appear word-initially. (4) VOWEL ALTERNATION: e varies [e]~[ɛ], o varies [o]~[ɔ] depending on stress and register. (5) DIPHTHONGS: ai=[aj], au=[aw]. (6) V: phoneme /v/ from Portuguese loanwords; absent in indigenous Austronesian vocabulary. (7) TETUN TERIK: rural traditional variety (Tetum Terik / Tetun Belu) has more conservative phonology and less Portuguese influence — this file models Tetun Praça.",
